posts.caption: "The image was taken while driving across The Alvord Desert in Oregon," the photographer Jono Melamed (@le_yone). "After a few rough months, I drove down to The Alvord to get away from everything that was holding me down at home in the city. There are no roads on the playa… No roads and no rules. So, I drove… Fast… With loud music playing and wind beating on my face. It was perfect and, for a brief moment, all of my problems melted away into the blur of the passing desert." The artist captions the image with this passage: "Sometimes it’s hard to remember that life is in front of you, even when you’re speeding away from the past." "I took this photo from a hotel room with a window overlooking the very center of Warsaw," Ada Zielińska (@adsoadsoadso) remembers. "It was November 11th, 2018, the day when Poland celebrated a century of independence. The gathering you can see from the window is the beggining of annual Independence March. For this occasion, I booked the room to stage this photo. A week earlier, I checked view from every floor in the hotel, and finally I decided on the 9th floor, room 919. The idea was to contrast the cosy interior with the vivid, loud and sometimes violent celebration. I asked the calmest person I know to pose for this photo, and suggested she to wear the most comfortable clothes. We entered the room, rearranged it so the bed was next to the window, and just waited there for Warsaw to dissapear in flares. I took two exposures from the room and put them into one photo." While she prefers not to comment politically, the viral photograph has been read by some as a reflection of current unease in Europe. "In 1996, after returning from the U.S.-Mexico border, I showed this photograph to Rebecca [Norris Webb], who I’d been seeing for some six months," Alex Webb (@webb_norriswebb) writes. "'Muy romantico,' she said, smiling bemusedly. Looking again at this photograph from Nuevo Laredo, Mexico, I began to see what she saw — that the image strikes a different note. Although inhabited by those deep shadows that characterize much of my Mexico work, this particular photograph is quieter, more lyrical. It’s as if its human moments — the couple embracing, the father holding his child — somehow manage to keep the darkness at bay, even if only briefly. Photographers don’t just find photographs; sometimes photographs find photographers. In retrospect, it hardly seems surprising that this photograph found me when it did — as I was falling for the remarkable woman and lyrical photographer who’s the love of my life. Three years later, we printed this photograph on our wedding invitations." This image is part of 'Slant Rhymes', a book of photography and poetry by Webb and Norris Webb. For more from the duo, be sure to follow along at @webb_norriswebb. "This photo was captured just a few nights ago after the first large snow of the season," Patrick McCormack (@patrick.mccormack) told us earlier this week. "The house seen here rests at the end of a cul-de-sac where my in-laws live. I’m currently prepping stuffing for Thanksgiving at their house so this same scene is still in sight and now even snowier. It has the essence of home, a theme running throughout a lot of my work lately." "Here, a Langur monkey feasts on flowers left by Indians from all over India after praying at Lake Pushkar during Diwali, the Hindu Festival of Lights," the photojournalist Russell Lee Klika (@rklika) writes of this image. He once told us, "Since retiring from the U.S.Army in 2014, I have continued to photograph as a means of therapy and have been wandering throughout Southeast Asia photographing indigenous tribes and festivals." We’re thrilled to have Nowhere Diary (@nowherediary) taking over our feed today! "With all the other feature accounts out there, I wanted to do something new,” the Danish photographer Kim Høltermand (@holtermand), who founded Nowhere Diary back in February, tells us. “I had this concept of a visual diary featuring moody, melancholic photography from both acclaimed and unknown photographers.” First up, we have this image from the book ‘House Hunting’ by Todd Hido (@toddhido_). “I take photographs of houses at night because I wonder about the families inside them,” Hido has said. “I wonder about how people live, and the act of taking that photograph is a meditation.” Stay tuned for more, and tag #nowherediary for a chance to be featured by Nowhere Diary. // #toddhido #contemporaryphotography #artphotography #popsofcolor #moodygrams #cinematicphotography #architecturedetail #surrealphotography #architexture #cinematic #mistyfoggymilkymoody #ontheroadagain #lowlight #americanroads #bluehour #nightmoves #architecture #nightphoto #nightphotography

"I’m currently doing a long bicycle trip from India to England, and this was shot in Arkhangai, Mongolia," the photographer Jeremy John (@jeremyj0hn) tells us. "I was camping by a river when a nomad from a nearby yurt came to my tent and beckoned me to follow him. Some way downstream of my tent there appeared two guys across the river holding some sheep. The nomad, named Billgunne, began one of several trips across to fetch the livestock one-by-one. My friend and I held the animals down in-between his lengths. Billgunne later told us that this particular sheep was getting old and had been selected for slaughter in the coming days. I think it’s safe to say she lived a full life wandering in the vastness Mongolian Steppe. The locals really care for their animals there."
